ges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William John Gurdon was born in 1259, in Dedham, Essex, England, United Kingdom as the son of John Gurdon. He had at least 1 son. He died on 3 April 1306, in his hometown, at the age of 47, and was buried in Dedham, Essex, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1259–3 April 1306":"1259–3. aprill 1306","1259–1306":"1259–1306","1285–1356":"1285–1356","1217–1287":"1217–1287","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","14 January 1287":"14. jaanuar 1287","1356":"1356","3 April 1306":"3. aprill 1306","1287":"1287","1285":"1285","1306":"1306","Dedham, Colchester Borough, Essex, England  Dedham, St Mary the Virgin":"Dedham, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dedham, Essex, England":"Dedham, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1259–3 April 1306":"1259–3. huhtikuuta 1306","1259–1306":"1259–1306","1285–1356":"1285–1356","1217–1287":"1217–1287","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","14 January 1287":"14. tammikuuta 1287","1356":"1356","3 April 1306":"3. huhtikuuta 1306","1287":"1287","1285":"1285","1306":"1306","Dedham, Colchester Borough, Essex, England  Dedham, St Mary the Virgin":"Dedham, Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Dedham, Essex, England":"Dedham, Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kun